post_text: Alden High School is very excited and eager to announce our partnership with Horizon Health Services. Professional tele-counseling services will be easily accessible for our students and families at Alden High School! We acknowledge that during these unprecedented times of uncertainty, our social-emotional well-being is our highest priority. This is why our partnership with Horizon Health Services couldn’t have come at a better time. Students will be able to access tele-therapy with an experienced clinical counselor, and they can work with the student/family schedule in order to find a time that works best (either during the school day in the Guidance Office or after school in the comfort of your home)! Please review the attached flyer, and if you would like to find out more information, feel free to contact the Alden Counseling Center at 716-937-9116 x4215.

Alden Central School will be providing FREE breakfasts and lunches to ALL school age children. Starting Thursday 3/19, they will be handing out breakfast/lunch on Monday’s and Thursday’s following 3/19. This Thursday you may pick up breakfast/lunch for that day and Friday.
Monday you may pick up breakfast/lunch for Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday.
If circumstances prevent you from being able to pick up, you may contact Anita Trautwein, Food Service Director at 937-9116 and arrange for your breakfast/lunch to be dropped off.
As Thursday closed in I will have more information on times of pick up.
Thank you to all the staff working tirelessly to provide food to our children (no matter income) at this trying time. #GOBULLDOGS

post_text:
The Alden High School yearbook staff is hard at work creating a unique and important book for each and every student. Made up of a dozen students the yearbook staff is always present at any important event in school. Including the many sports events, show productions, class competitions, clubs, and homecoming events the yearbook staff is all over it getting the best coverage and scoop for the book.

This year the yearbook is specially designed for Vision 2020. High School is an important part of our lives. The memories we make throughout the years help shape us into the young adults were growing up to be. Having a book to highlight those events will act as a way to cherish our memories when we’re older.

To buy a yearbook you can visit http://jostensyearbooks.com
Order yours by January 31st, 2020

September 18, 2017 at 12:19 PM ·

HAPPY HOMECOMING WEEK ALDEN! While the HS will be celebrating with spirit days and special events all week, here's a quick rundown of the week for our community events:

- Homecoming Parade (Thursday 9/21 @ 6:15pm)
- Pep Rally @ Athletic Field (Thursday 9/21 following Parade)
- PowderPuff Football @ Athletic Field (Thursday 9/21 following rally)
- Wall of Fame Induction Ceremony (Friday 9/22 @ 6pm)
(Inductees: Tyler Stoldt, Elizabeth Giest, and the 1977 Rifle Team)
- Homecoming Football Game vs Cheektowaga (Friday 9/22 @ 7:30pm)

post_text: On Monday, March 27, 2017 in the Wilson Conrad Auditorium, family and friends gathered to witness the induction of the 13 newest members of the Alpha Chapter of the Alden High School National Honor Society. Katy DeFilippo, a 1996 graduate and member of NHS, was the keynote speaker. Students are invited to join National Honor Society after an extensive application process that looks heavily at the four pillars of NHS: scholarship, leadership, character, and service. Members must maintain an overall grade point average of 91% and are required to complete a variety of service hours throughout the local school community.

post_text:
Mrs. Wilson's class and 2nd grade students from Mrs. Ponichtera, Mrs. Etzel and Mrs. Ritchie's class used Apple TV and an iPad to FaceTime with Dr. Richard Ronan. He lives in Winchester, VA. and is a chemist who formerly worked for the Environmental Protection Agency.

Dr. Ronan excitedly taught the students that "Science is everywhere!" He also shared that kids are like scientists when they take steps to solve problems in their everyday life. He posed the question, "How might we solve the problem of being hungry?" One way was to grow our own food.

The lesson concluded with an experiment involving students planting tomato seeds in miniature green houses. They were excited to learn from a long distance expert and look forward to watching their tomato plants thrive!

post_text: The Alden Robotics Team, “the CosmoBots”, were awarded a $4,000 grant from Ingersoll Rand after a competitive application process. Nathan Vetter and Vito Lorenzi, engineers at Ingersoll Rand and graduates of Alden High School, presented the donation to the team. The team gave a brief robot demonstration along with a presentation to the board, and the donors, about their recent achievements in the Robotics Competitions and their plan for spending the money to improve STEM outreach in our school community.
text: The Alden Robotics Team, “the CosmoBots”, were awarded a $4,000 grant from Ingersoll Rand after a competitive application process. Nathan Vetter and Vito Lorenzi, engineers at Ingersoll Rand and graduates of Alden High School, presented the donation to the team. The team gave a brief robot demonstration along with a presentation to the board, and the donors, about their recent achievements in the Robotics Competitions and their plan for spending the money to improve STEM outreach in our school community.

post_text: After learning about natural erosion and deposition, kids in Mrs. Etzel's & Mrs. Ponichtera's 2nd grade class are studying differences soil types and conditions. They are trying to learn ways people can alter the soil in order to reduce the amount of erosion. We measure the amount of erosion and deposition that occurs over time after water is added to sandy soil, clay soil, rocky soil, and soil. Here's to our future scientists!
